tip.text:
That vegan cafe in Bethnal Green everyone is raving about. You've heard of it. We're sure you have. It's 100% vegan, community run and not for profit. Get your vegan samosas, sausage rolls, cakes and milkshakes, or go for a posh coffee.

You can also buy produce to take away, including vegan cheeses, faux meats, tofu, tempeh, Club Mate & Fritz Kola (German drinks), as well as politically-charged vegan cookbooks. Because you never know when you might need one. Hell, you could probably use one right now.

To all those who think vegans don't do it indulgent we present: We Are Vegan Everything. A very Insta friendly, Bali-vibes brunch spot and cafe in Hackney that's doing mighty, naughty things with plant-based food. We came in for brunch and were really damn satisfied by both the sweet (blueberry pancakes and vegan coconut cream) and savoury (sourdough topped with tomatoes, mushrooms and avocado). It feels like the kind of place an Australian wellness influencer in Bali would have created, and we mean that in a nice way. The freakshake, meanwhile, is one of the most rich and decadent shakes we've ever sampled.

If youre wondering if this Breaking Bad-themed cocktail bar is all gimmick, we should say: it is. But it has enough attention to detail, enough interactivity, and enough cool shit going on that it transcends what could just exist as a clickbait FB video and becomes a place that we might actually recommend. The whole thing is built into an RV truck like the one from the show; youll don yellow safety suits, grab a welcome cocktail of crystal meth (a mojito in a flask with a syringe of blue liquid) and take a seat somewhere in the meth lab caravan. The menu takes you straight back to your GCSEs with Bunsen burners, test tubes, and neon-coloured alcoholic beverages.

The cocktails are a little sweet for our tastes but the fun here is the spectacle: using dry ice to create vanilla smoke to infuse our peach liquor with; using syringes and an electric pump to make white chocolate foam; and best/weirdest of all - a bowl of Kahla-milk Rice Crispies. Its an experience, and for 35 quid for two hours and three cocktails, is just inside the realms of not a bump.

Outside of the RV theyve got another bar, vegan pizzas, a pumping hip hop soundtrack, and arcade machines where youll be awarded a shot depending on your score. Oh, and the whole place is vegan. Seriously theres a lot going on at this place, and were still trying to wrap our heads around it all. Or maybe we actually just took meth and this was all some fever-dream. Is anyone else itchy?

listing.name: Dark Arts Coffee / I Will Kill Again
listing.subtitle: Roastery and Cafe

tip.text:
Some sort of enigmatic magic is afoot in a railway arch in Homerton, where an alluring mishmash of the occult, biker culture and insanely good coffee is turning people a little bit crazy - although it could just be that jitter juice. A roastery during the week (Dark Arts Coffee); a vegan-orientated cafe on the weekends (I Will Kill Again), we rate this as a really memorable place to do the coffee and brunch thing in East.

The coffee is dangerously moreish: beans from all over the world that are uniquely blended into something so damn creamy you can almost taste the threat of your own demise. The brunch, meanwhile, is of the quality to have vegans and non-vegans alike rushing down to get into plates that artfully combine smoked tempeh rashers, crispy potato rosti and sweet sun-dried tomatoes to create something greater than the sum of their parts. Throw in a chilled ambience with laid-back, black-clad owners dripping with cool, and you have yourself a spot that walks the walk and talks the talk.

Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle - House of Hackney (used to be called House of Seitan), with their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, completely blew up social media as they opened their doors for hoards of hungry herbivores.

Cheekily situated next to a butcher's shop (and with queues that put that butcher's shop to shame), the Seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Whether you're a flexitarian, participating in Veganuary, or stay meat-free year round, it's nice to know that you can now indulge in your favourite comfort food without compromising your morals.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

No way are the vegan wizards behind The Brook about to sacrifice flavour in their pursuit of plant-based pleasure - this is as close to vegan junk food as we've found in London. It's a vegan tapas restaurant and cocktail bar; a suitably laid-back, friendly and DIY-chic space where vegans and curious non-vegans enter the doors to see what's next in the vegolution. The answer: pretty nice grub with a surprising and satisfying indulgence about it.

The tip is to share five or six of their tapas dishes between two - and let us point you towards the moreish sesame chick'n skewers; the bountiful and comforting jackfruit quesadillas; and a zingy lime and coconut dal. Portion sizes are not huge - and potentially a pound or two over what we'd like - but given the meticulous R&D and care gone into creating each dish, we're prepared to make allowances.

The cocktails here are also not a simple add-on. Their huge choice of converted classics and house specials are put on the same footing as the food - meaning that whilst hungry foodies frequent the front and tuck into the tasty bits, the bar area and tables at the back create an altogether looser vibe.

As the classic riches to rags tale goes, Stephen left his big ol' corporate job for a small foodie dream; setting up shop in London Fields to cater to the growing number of Mare Street vegans. Buffalo has all the fast-food-style edibles you'd expect to find in a vegan diner coupled with an easy going atmosphere, an indie playlist and some downright friendly staff (Maybe eating veggies makes you happier.)

Like many a vegan menu before it, this one was a little hit-and-miss on our visit, with fairly standard plant-based burgers and the like. The sides, however, were banging. Buffalo cauliflower wings were to die for and cheesey truffle fries, kimchi fries and broccoli with tahini won us over too. We'd probably pop back in for the sides alone, those and the mighty moreish bottled negronis.

Owned by the enigmatic King Cook, this London Fields spot is a favourite of grime outfit Boy Better Know with JME a regular fixture. King Cook's taken a millennial approach to veganism, with no preachy, dreadlocked crusties on site and a menu perfect for meat eaters and vegans alike. There's a dish called High Grade - a bowl of hemp oil stir-fried veggies in sweet and sour BBQ sauce, topped with green herbs and hemp seed crumbles - which should tell you all you need to know.

The menu is mostly taken up by creamy Thai curries and gingery noodle dishes, with a few nods to multicultural London: there's a tofu scramble full English, a few Jamaican goodies, a Yoga Fire (turmeric dahl), and a provencal garlicky, herby, truffle oil number too. Further up the scale of healthiness than a lot of East London vegan fast-food spots, a lot more delish' and with 100% more street cred; we've got a lotta time for Cook Daily.

For a place with so much footfall, the selection of eateries on Broadway Market is surprisingly not all that. Baba Souks, however, is a relaxing and welcoming cafe well worth an excursion to. Stepping through the door here you'll be greeted with a welcoming smile, Arabian rugs, a pleasing amount of terracotta and greenery and a melodic Middle Eastern soundtrack. London Fields becomes languid Tel Aviv.

It's almost always a relaxed vibe here where you're grabbing coffee, brunch, a takeaway lunchtime wrap or an evening shared platter featuring all that good, reliable, Middle Eastern produce. The Baba sharing platter, coming it at a just about reasonable 20, was a hearty and healthy-tasting combination of flavours with poached eggs, halloumi, falafel, hummus, moutabel, and a couple of things we couldnt immediately identify. Ask no questions, just dip your sourdough or crudit in and munch on those trustworthy, dependable flavours.

Love Shack feels like it would be better suited to a hedonistic patch on a sunny Thai island rather than the particularly un-exotic Cambridge Heath. Set up by three friends and very much a passion project, it's a vegan restaurant and hangout space where live music, cocktails, yoga, dogs and hammocks can all be found at different times. It's zero-waste and zero-wastemen: this is a good-vibes-only operation.

Located in two arches, it's got an appropriately ramshackle feel to it with the feeling it could all collapse at any moment. And we dig that. Food is served throughout the day, drinks in the evening whilst the outdoor area makes for a superb chilling spot when the summer sun rears its head.

A longtime neighbourhood stalwart, the Gallery Cafe is beloved for its well-priced vegan and vegetarian food and community spirit. There's a whole heap of art on the walls and a stand up programme of events including book clubs and open mic nights.

It can get a tad busy here, but it's cosy as all heck. Come for hearty veggie breakfasts - we lapped up our full vegan english and oat milk latte without any trouble.

We're still treating our PTSD from the bygone era of vegetarian restaurants, when a dinner meant a fossilised falafel ball on a bed of grass. Oh, how far we've come. Stokey Veg Vegan is part of the new wave of meat-free restos, serving creative, delicious small plates that, despite their moderate price tag, wouldn't be out of place at a big-name eatery in Marlyebone.

The interior is modest, and the focus is firmly on the food. It's a labour of love - after doing stints at restaurants in Spain, Japan, and London, head chef Daniele Aloi opened Stokey Veg Vegan to showcase his supreme skills with stuff that grows from the ground. The (extensive) menu changes frequently, but you can expect Japanese-influences and meticulously-balanced flavours. We had a creamy burrata with fresh black truffle and figs, an umami-drenched aubergine with a den miso glaze, crispy fried courgette flowers with a salivate-y ricotta filling, and lots more. Jealous?

Our friendly local vegetarians can have a real tough time of it, apart from the constant quizzing and questioning, dining out in the city is a real minefield. That's why Mildreds (everyone's favourite veggie resto) is on a mission to colonise the entirety of London. Number four, in Dalston, has all the same colour and wholesomeness on its menu, but with a slightly swisher East London look.

There's plenty a fresh healthy salad of course, but lots of warming curries and Mexican bean mixes too. There's all manner of comfort on the brunch menu - think blueberry waffles or eggs in different outfits, and the only blood you'll see is in the word bloody Mary. Order cocktails, wine and beer at will but if you're really stuffing in your 5 (*ahem* 7) a day then fresh juice should be the top pick for you.

Is the rapid spread of the 'small, sharing plates' trend doing your nut in? Well what better way to revolt than by getting rid of plates all together? Andu is the perfect spot to do so - this Kingsland Road gem is one of those no-bullshit places that serves up simple and delicious Ethiopian food which also happens to be 100% vegan. It's BYOB, the staff are bloody lovely and its damn cheap to boot. And as is the way with Ethiopian cuisine, the food is served atop injera bread (sour fermented pancake).

Wed recommend grabbing a pal and rolling down to Dalston to try the sampler, a selection of six dishes served atop injera or rice - perfect for two to share and yours for only 12. If youre in the area and dining Han Solo, you can get an individual sampler to take away for a fiver. So leave any vibe-snipers at home and get yourself down to Andu before you can say yemisir wot (Ethiopian red lentil stew).

There's definitely not a shortage of killer cocktail joints on Dalston Kingsland High Street, but it seems the guys behind The Alibi and Birthdays like some healthy competition.

Fill your boots with delicious cocktails and nibbles from their light-snack menu. We're definitely going for a Des Barres - jalapeo infused vodka, kiwi juice & coconut ice cubes which has jalapeo infused vodka, kiwi juice and coconut ice cubes - o00o0h la la. All the cocktails are animal free, they even use chickpea water instead of egg white for that sexy frothy look.

What's afoot in the kitchen? Well there's a rotating line up of vegan pop ups on so check their site for deets.

A true Stokey stalwart, Rasa has been dishing out vegetarian Keralan food since back when Jeremy Corbyn was the only veggie in North London (circa 1997). Its bright pink walls, furniture and decor have become synonymous in our minds with the hearty and authentic South Indian flavours they deal with.

Well known favourites like daal and tangy tomato curries sit alongside some more experimental numbers like the beet cheera pachadi, a spinach-beet blend with roasted coconut, mustard seeds and curry leaves. Theyre all flavoursome, colourful and super cheap. For mopping up duties youre gonna need a paratha (flakier than your old school mates) and a masala dosa (basically a giant crispy pancake filled with potato curry).

address.line1: Here East, Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park

tip.text: Mother Juice Works hard making smooth smoothies, healthy juices and vegan foods. She feeds Hackney's yogis, yummy mummies and hippies, those wondrous freaks of nature who manage to eat healthy on a daily. The kind who salivate over reclaimed wood, hanging plants, and intricate combinations like beetroot, carrot, pineapple, apple, grapefruit, lemon and ginger juice; or coconut lentil dahl with crispy sweet potatoes; or the crme de la crme, the raw cookie dough balls. And who can blame 'em. It tastes good, it looks good, it feels good. What more do you want?

Dani and Vane, both from Venezuela, both vegans, both into baking - seems like a match made in plant-based heaven. They started off baking out of their home taking orders on Instagram, followed by a pop up shop, then finally this permanent home on Brick Lane. The small and bright venue is prime Insta fodder, with saccharine decor, and cutesy pink quotes - a big trend we've noticed in the vegan world recently.

Cakes are made in all sorts of towering rainbows, layered chocolate and dainty cupcake varieties, to varying degrees of success. We saw very little sign of lemon in the lemon curd but could easily have doubled up on the banoffee. There's also a soy-based soft serve which you can have in a cup covered in sprinkles, or sandwiched between two photogenic peanut butter cookies. Snap, snap, snap.

We're starting to think this whole vegan craze is a big conspiracy. Is London's mayoral office in bed with the oat milk industry? Whatever dark deeds are going on behind the scenes, we're down with it, and we're down with the Vurger Co.'s above ave plant-based burgers. No desert-dry black bean dust here - these boys are moist and primed for some lip smackin'.

Try the MLT, a smoky number made with roasted shrooms and borlotti beans, and topped with house-made sun dried tomato and walnut pesto; or the summer-ready Holy Habanero, a corn fritter patty piled high with spiced almonds, crispy tortillas, and house-made habanero mayo. Their sweet potato fries are also crisped and spiced the way we like 'em. All makes for perfectly worthy fast food fare.
